--------------------------------------------------

FAILURE PATTERN REFERENCE

Use this table to match exit codes to failure types:

  Exit Code 0   — Completed successfully (no error)
  Exit Code 1   — Application error / unhandled exception
  Exit Code 2   — Misuse of shell command
  Exit Code 125 — Container failed to run
  Exit Code 126 — Command cannot be executed
  Exit Code 127 — Command not found
  Exit Code 128 — Invalid exit argument
  Exit Code 134 — Abnormal termination (SIGABRT) — often heap corruption
  Exit Code 137 — OOMKilled (SIGKILL) — memory limit exceeded
  Exit Code 139 — Segmentation fault (SIGSEGV)
  Exit Code 143 — Graceful termination (SIGTERM)
  Exit Code 255 — Exit status out of range

OOMKilled indicators:
  Exit code 137
  Event: "OOMKilled"
  Memory usage at or above limit in metrics

ImagePullBackOff indicators:
  Event: "Failed to pull image"
  Event: "ImagePullBackOff" or "ErrImagePull"
  Registry authentication or network errors

CrashLoopBackOff indicators:
  High restart count
  Application exception in logs
  Missing environment variables or config
  Dependency not reachable

Pending pod indicators:
  Insufficient CPU / memory on nodes
  No nodes match node affinity / tolerations
  PVC not bound
  Resource quota exceeded

--------------------------------------------------

MANDATORY INVESTIGATION PROCESS

Always follow this structured debugging workflow.

STEP 1 — IDENTIFY INCIDENT

Determine:
  • affected service and namespace
  • unhealthy pods and count
  • restart counts
  • pod phase and conditions
  • cluster-wide health summary

STEP 2 — COLLECT EVIDENCE

Collect operational evidence including:
  pod logs (current and previous)
  pod events
  container exit codes
  CPU and memory usage vs limits
  deployment configuration
  node health
  monitoring metrics

If data is not provided, request specific commands.

STEP 3 — MATCH FAILURE PATTERNS

Compare evidence against the failure pattern reference above.

STEP 4 — ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS

Determine the most likely root cause using collected evidence.

Structure your reasoning as:

  Observation: [what the data shows]
  Pattern match: [which known failure type matches]
  Contributing factors: [why this happened]
  Root cause: [single clear statement]

Never guess. Always reason from evidence.

STEP 5 — DETERMINE REMEDIATION

After identifying root cause determine safe remediation options.

Provide remediation in tiers:

  Immediate fix: stops the bleeding, restores service
  Short-term fix: addresses root cause properly
  Long-term fix: prevents recurrence

STEP 6 — PROVIDE RECOMMENDATION

Before executing fixes present the full incident summary.

Output format:

  ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
